</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,570,847]" pageId="3" pageNumber="300">
I should make a clarification on another matter concerned in 
<bibRefCitation author="Kosterin, O. E." box="[870,1045,606,631]" pageId="3" pageNumber="300" pagination="561 - 575" refId="ref5092" refString="Kosterin, O. E. (2018) Rediscovery of Lestes nigriceps Fraser, 1924 (Odonata: Lestidae) in eastern Cambodia. Zootaxa, 4526 (4), 561 - 575. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4526.4.8" type="journal article" year="2018">Kosterin (2018)</bibRefCitation>
. Matti Hämäläinen kindly informed me that the number of 366 species described by C.H. Fraser, which I cited in 
<bibRefCitation author="Kosterin, O. E." box="[988,1159,642,667]" pageId="3" pageNumber="300" pagination="561 - 575" refId="ref5092" refString="Kosterin, O. E. (2018) Rediscovery of Lestes nigriceps Fraser, 1924 (Odonata: Lestidae) in eastern Cambodia. Zootaxa, 4526 (4), 561 - 575. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4526.4.8" type="journal article" year="2018">Kosterin (2018)</bibRefCitation>
according to 
<bibRefCitation author="Wasscher, M. &amp; Dumont, H. J." pageId="3" pageNumber="300" pagination="369 - 402" refId="ref5329" refString="Wasscher, M. &amp; Dumont, H. J. (2013) Life and work of Michel Edmond de Selys Lonchamps (1813 - 1900), the founder of Odonatology. Odonatologica, 42 (4), 369 - 402." type="journal article" year="2013">Wasscher &amp; Dumont (2013)</bibRefCitation>
, was strongly underestimated. 
<bibRefCitation author="Kimmins, D. E." box="[642,818,678,702]" pageId="3" pageNumber="300" pagination="173 - 227" refId="ref5038" refString="Kimmins, D. E. (1966) A list of the Odonata types described by F. C. Fraser, now in the British Museum (Natural History). Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Entomology, 18 (6), 173 - 227." type="journal article" year="1966">Kimmins (1966)</bibRefCitation>
mentioned 562 species group names described by him and although some of them proposed in a subspecific rank, the number of those described as species (not necessarily considered as valid species at present) was surely more than five hundred.
</paragraph>
